       TAXI  As in any other metropolis, Buenos Aires is also full of taxis and the ride is very cheap. (The initial meter rate starts at 1.44 pesos.)&nbsp;Radio taxis&nbsp;are common in the city as well as Remises, which are private cars. They cost almost the same amount as the regular taxis, and you can reserve a cab any time or any place you want, and you can&nbsp;know how much&nbsp;you'll pay beforehand.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  &nbsp;   BUS  Buses are called Collectivos. Once you arrive in the city you will realize that&nbsp;they are everywhere. There are more than 140 lines and you can get to any destination&nbsp;using the Collectivos. It's&nbsp;also the cheapest way to travel around the city since each ride&nbsp;costs&nbsp;btw 0.30-1.25&nbsp;pesos. Don't forget though that buses only accept coins and you have to tell the driver your destination first thing when you step in the bus. To learn the right routes for you, stop at any tourist information booth and tell them where you want to go. They'll draw you a map and give you the bus #.  &nbsp;   SUBWAY  The subway system in Buenos Aires is also very convenient. It's called the Subte. The ride costs 0.70 cents and unlike other major cities of the world, the subway is very clean.&nbsp;  you can check out the&nbsp;Subte Map clicking on the link below:  &nbsp;   urlLink http://www.metrovias.com.ar/eng/contenido/contenido.asp?id_cat=35&amp;articulo=&amp;opcion=Maps&amp;estilo=14&amp;id_cont=168&amp;link=&amp;cate=&amp;manual=1 &nbsp; 
    


